<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-666-379  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 666 379.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 3 1990 v24 n49 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>4GL vs. 3GL: a debate rages without meaning. (fourth generationlanguages; third generation languages)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Howard, Keith.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The debate between the proponents of fourth- and third-generationlanguages (4GLs and 3GLs) needs to be laid to rest.andP;  The term'4GL,' wrongly implies an evolutionary step beyond 3GLs.andP;  Inreality, a 4GL is a user-tunable application based on a 3GL, whichin turn is a full-service programming language.andP;  Most 4GLs ride ontop of relational databases, having been specifically designed tofront end such data repositories.andP;  A 4GL is better suited forusers with relatively simple applications needs.andP;  A 3GL is thechoice for users who need the flexibility to develop new, complexapplications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fourth-Generation LanguagesThird GenerationUser NeedsApplications Programming.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>